YELLOW FEVER - AMERICAS (09): BRAZIL, MONKEYS
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Rio de Janeiro state
[2] Sao Paulo state

******
[1] Rio de Janeiro state
Date: Sat 27 Jan 2018
Source: El Mañana [in Spanish trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://elmanana.com.mx/noticia/159316/Matan-a-131-monos-en-Brasil-por-panico-de-fiebre-amarilla.html


A least 131 monkeys died since the beginning of the year [2018] in Rio de Janeiro, the majority (69 percent) because of humans, an official source said this Saturday [27 Jan 2018], who connect the bad luck of these animals with the unfounded fear that they could aggravate the yellow fever outbreak which has been registered in this Brazilian state.

The 69 percent of the animals collected in Rio had signs of human attacks through clubbing or poisoning, said the Subsecretariat of Surveillance, Health Inspection and Zoonoses Control (SUBVISA). SUBVISA stated that of the 131 dead monkeys, 32 were found in the City of Rio, the regional capital.

Environmental organization officials worry about these data and point out that the monkeys are allies for the eradication of yellow fever since they help identify the areas in which the virus is present, but do not transmit it to humans. Yellow fever [virus] can only be acquired by the bite of an infected mosquito, something that is unknown to the population, the specialists said.

Given this situation, the Green Line, a platform for issuing complaints by telephone in the Rio municipality for environmental crimes, initiated a campaign against attacks on monkeys in which those who know of an episode are invited to call or send in photographs and videos, while always guaranteed anonymity. The complaints that are received are sent to the Command of Environmental Police and the Commission for Environmental Protection, according to the municipality.

The states of Rio de Janeiro and Sao Paulo this Thursday [25 Jan 2018] initiated campaigns to intensify vaccination, confronting the increasing number of cases of the disease, which terrify those who live in these regions.

Although the Brazilian health authorities insist on reassuring [everyone] that a yellow fever outbreak does not exist, [human] deaths jumped from 20 to 53 in one week, and the number of cases of the disease increased to 130, according to the latest data from the Ministry of Health.

The most affected states are: Minas Gerais, with 24 [human] deaths, Sao Paulo with 21, and Río de Janeiro with 8, according to official statistics.

--
